{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Ba9Cbz3pchMNiRBA4Fbu4V","type":"tool_result","content":"  5200→## 5. What Went Wrong\n  5201→\n  5202→- **Ralph state corruption — 35 sessions wasted.** The single biggest problem of the sprint. Ralph's in-memory state snapshot predates story completion, and every session it overwrites `sprint-state.json`, reverting 4 stories from done to review. Each session detects and fixes this, consuming API calls for zero value.\n  5203→- **Retro file bloat.** The session retro file has grown to 268KB (5,094 lines), exceeding the 256KB read limit. Each no-op session appended to it, compounding the problem.\n  5204→- **Verification cost dominance.** Verification consumed 53.3% of total sprint cost ($472). While thoroughness is valuable, the ratio suggests over-verification or inefficient verification workflows.\n  5205→- **Phantom story cost.** The `1-1-foo` phantom story consumed $24.35 in API calls before being identified and blocked.\n  5206→\n  5207→## 6. Lessons Learned\n  5208→\n  5209→1. **State management needs monotonic guarantees.** Story status should only move forward (backlog -> dev -> review -> done), never backward. A one-line guard (`if current === done, skip write`) would have prevented 35 wasted sessions.\n  5210→2. **Verification is the most expensive phase.** At 53% of cost, verification workflow efficiency is the highest-leverage optimization target for the next sprint.\n  5211→3. **Retro files need rotation or size limits.** Appending to a single file across 50+ sessions creates an unreadable artifact. Future sprints should rotate per-session or cap file size.\n  5212→4. **First-pass success validates the review pipeline.** The code-review -> fix -> verify pipeline worked flawlessly today. The review phase catches bugs cheaply; verification confirms. This two-phase approach should be preserved.\n  5213→5. **Ralph's state snapshot model is fundamentally flawed.** Loading state once at startup and writing it back on every loop creates a \"last writer wins\" race condition. The fix is either event-sourced state or read-before-write with version checks.\n  5214→\n  5215→## 7. Action Items\n  5216→\n  5217→| # | Action | Priority | Scope |\n  5218→|---|--------|----------|-------|\n  5219→| 1 | Add monotonic status guard to Ralph: never revert a `done` story | HIGH | ralph/ |\n  5220→| 2 | Rotate retro files per-session or impose size cap | MEDIUM | harness tooling |\n  5221→| 3 | Audit verification phase for cost reduction (redundant test runs, over-reading) | MEDIUM | verification workflow |\n  5222→| 4 | Remove or prevent phantom story creation (`1-1-foo` pattern) | LOW | state management |\n  5223→| 5 | Fix 5 pre-existing BATS failures in `all_tasks_complete` suite | LOW | tests |\n  5224→| 6 | Address LOW-priority code review items deferred from epic 16 stories | LOW | tech debt backlog |\n  5225→\n  5226→## Final Note\n  5227→\n  5228→This is the FINAL session retrospective for the codeharness sprint. The sprint is complete. All code is committed, all stories verified, all epics closed. The primary takeaway: the autonomous execution pipeline works end-to-end, but Ralph's state management bug consumed significant resources and should be the first fix in any follow-up work.\n  5229→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01DS4p4h17YJcocDEtENBbe4","session_id":"7ea5f697-8411-4b70-a21e-041b4c52ed05","uuid":"9981fee9-0fe3-48c1-a9be-0f23a7b020d4","timestamp":"2026-03-28T12:58:06.620Z"}
